oh, do we want a new file here? That's a huge import increase.

> oh, do we want a new file here? That's a huge import increase.

@j-loreaux would it make sense to put these results in `Analysis/Normed/Lp/ProdLp` instead?
If the import increase there is small, and it doesn't make the file too long, then sure.

> If the import increase there is small, and it doesn't make the file too long, then sure.

I've broken everything apart from the last two results (`idemFst_Lprojection` and `idemSnd_Lprojection`) out into a separate PR #21899 on the grounds that it's more general than L-Projections - the results hold for seminorms and `p : ‚Ñù‚â•0‚àû`. I'm fairly certain now that those results belong in `Analysis/Normed/Lp/ProdLp`.

It may become more obvious where to put `idemFst_Lprojection` and `idemSnd_Lprojection` when the theory is a bit further developed (#14369).

minor comments, please request review after responding and we'll get it merged.
I've split this to #20383, along with a bunch of related lemmas.
Thanks!
Now that we have a simple proof of `prod_norm_eq_add_idemFst`, I've just used that result rather than treat `p = 1` as a special case.
This lemma shouldn't exist; the arguments to `+` are not well-typed here.

Do you mean it should be something like:
```
@[simp]
theorem mk_add_mk (a‚ÇÅ a‚ÇÇ : Œ±) (b‚ÇÅ b‚ÇÇ : Œ≤) :
    (WithLp.equiv p (Œ± √ó Œ≤)).symm (a‚ÇÅ, b‚ÇÅ) + (WithLp.equiv p (Œ± √ó Œ≤)).symm (a‚ÇÇ, b‚ÇÇ) =
      (WithLp.equiv p (Œ± √ó Œ≤)).symm (a‚ÇÅ + a‚ÇÇ, b‚ÇÅ + b‚ÇÇ) := rfl
```
?
Thanks for fixing this.

```suggestion
lemma idemFst_apply (x : WithLp p (Œ± √ó Œ≤)) : idemFst x = (WithLp.equiv _ _).symm (x.1, 0) := rfl

lemma idemSnd_apply (x : WithLp p (Œ± √ó Œ≤)) : idemSnd x = (WithLp.equiv _ _).symm (0, x.2) := rfl

```

I'd be inclined to write this as
```suggestion
    ‚Äñx‚Äñ = ‚ÄñidemFst x‚Äñ ‚äî ‚ÄñidemSnd x‚Äñ := by
```
which is shorter and more symmetric. Same below.
`P` and `1-P` tends to be the L-projection way of doing things, but I can see why `Fst` and `Snd` makes sense in this case.
I claim the L-projection way of doing things is now `IsLprojection` :)
Can you add the version started with `+` too, and the version with Fst and Snd swapped?
Done.
I think it would be reasonable to add an L1-only copy of this lemma, since I believe we have such a copy for WithLp.prod_norm_eq_add?
Yes, `WithLp.prod_norm_eq_of_L1` - thought I'd done that, but must have forgot.

```suggestion
@[simp]
lemma idemFst_add_idemSnd :
```
Do we use this `compl` naming elsewhere for `1 - P`? Normally `compl` refers to `·∂ú`. I'm not necessarily opposed to it, but it would be nice to have precedent.

The docstring for `HasCompl` says that it's for set or lattice complement:
https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/master/Mathlib/Order/Notation.lean#L30

Mathlib uses it quite extensively for Boolean Algebras, see for example https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/master/Mathlib/Order/BooleanAlgebra.lean#L570-L680
I think we generally phrase this as `max`? It's possible that's changed though.

Indeed, that's how I defined M-projection https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/5f7473608e12b27d4243ad79486918027c7082dd/Mathlib/Analysis/NormedSpace/MStructure.lean#L82 . I've changed this to `max`.
